			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I'd go with MW's suggestion on this one. I understand your perfectionism, believe me (!), but your time will be much better spent doing other mapping tasks like tweaking layout and item placement. Especially if it's a DM level, players will be engaged in too many other distracting actions to notice something like minor lighting anomalies, whereas they <span style="font-style: italic">will</span> notice unbalanced gameplay <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="Smile" border="0" /> 
<br />

<br />
In general, though, lighting can indeed be a pain in the arse and suck up a lot of mapping time -- it just takes a while to get a feel for doing it right first time (as mappers like Maric can), and it's not helped by the fact that you have to wait a while for each compile to go through...  If the shadowing is really bugging you, then I would suggest playing around with light entities that have low 'light' and '_fade' values (the latter parameter requiring ArghRad).</span><span class=sign><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://awakening2.planetquake.gamespy.com" target="_blank" class="postlink">Q2: Awakening II mod</a>
<br />
<a href="http://musashi.planetquake.gamespy.com" target="_blank" class="postlink">Q2: Maps and mods</a></span><span class="gensmall"></span>
                  <br /><br />
